				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Illusive</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">also jhorry the way mimic is coded to work, it needs to have the (energy)feedback in order to know which base damage ability to base itself off of.<br />
<br />
thats why all arcane spells provide feedback, so that when we crit and go to use mimic the game knows what our previous spell cast was.  This is also why we cant use mimic with any of the other nukes.<br />
<br />
so if you remove the arcane feedback from CV you remove its ability to utilize mimic, so I think that definately has to stay there for now.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
Doh now i remeber reading that!<br />
<br />
Man, i hope they clean up the coding with that. Having a &quot;previous cast&quot; registery, &quot;previous crit&quot; registery, and a &quot;last spell countered&quot; registery would help a lot wtih designing classes and abilities (especially the counter spell mechanics i mentioned)<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Illusive</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">
The other consideration with giving CV a re-use time, is psi's.  They currently have a lesser version of CV &quot;thought pulse&quot; which deals a greater amount of damage to them (about 30% more than we take) with a 4second re-use timer on it.<br />
<br />
I know already that giving sorc a longer re-cast on cv without modifiying the psi one, will cause a lot of miffed sorc's when the psi gets thought pulse up higher than cv because they have 1 more chance to ramp up the damage over a sorc.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
I have actually thought of this one because to me having two almost identable spells is not a good thing for diversity in play styles.<br />
<br />
I actually did a large post in the psionicist forums explaining some alternatives, so dont worry im spreading the headaches around to all the casters guys <img src="images/smilies/biggrin.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Big Grin" class="inlineimg" /><br />
<br />
In a nut shell, i described how to change Thought Pulse back to its original concept of a &quot;wind down&quot; nuke rather than the &quot;wind up&quot; nukes like Chaos Volley.<br />
<br />
Here was the reasoning:<br />
<br />
&quot;The psionicist stores up mental energy, and violently releases it in a powerful, condensed blast. Each reoccuring blast will be weaker, as the psionicist has not had time to regain this mental energy. It takes longer to recover with each successive use, and the physical strain on the psionicist is intense.&quot;<br />
<br />
Basically, imagine thought pulse as dealing 5000 damage instantly, but each cast after that is reduced by 25%.<br />
<br />
The 25% reductions can accumulate, and the ability checks for the most reacient one to apply the next stage of the reduction:<br />
<br />
So if TP is cast once, you get the normal 20 second wait for the spell, but if you cast TP again while this 20 waiting period is in effect, it will do 75% damage and will get the next TP &quot;weakend&quot; state, which lasts for 30 seconds instead of 20, then the next and final one would weaken it another 25% and last for a minute. 500 energy and health with each cast.<br />
<br />
So if spammed back to back:<br />
<br />
1 TP = wait 20 seconds = 5000 damage.<br />
2 TP = wait 30 seconds after second cast, = 8750<br />
3 TP = wait 60 seconds after 3rd cast, = 11,250<br />
<br />
if spaced out over 60 seconds:<br />
<br />
Wait 20 seconds between each TP, 4 TP's doing 20,000<br />
<br />
How much damage can chaos Volley do in a minute? Im trying to get thought pulse a bit under CV's damage, and have them deal this damage very differently.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Illusive</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">
Currently we have 4 chances if we get a resist spamming CV to continue to ramp up the damage. or it gets reset.  I dont think many of us like the idea of having the restriction of the re-cast timer on CV.<br /></div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
Understandable. Would the higher resist chance on CV help keep it more situational rather than universal? As in, in some contient it might not be a pactical spell, but in most contient it might be the best spell in our arsinal?<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Illusive</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">
The way CV currently is set up with the 10sec window, nothing's stopping you from casting other spells during cv's feedback cycle (taq's or FS or finishers) and then hitting cv again before the timer runs out.<br />
<br />
I see CV okay in its current itteration, once falling star and taq's are brought up to par.<br />
<br />
At that point we'll be able to do cv &gt; taq's &gt; FS &gt; cv &gt; taq &gt; FS &gt; and at any time we crit utilize our fire finishers and our cold finishers, while we slowly ramp up cv's damage, in otherwords if you wanted to you have the *choice* (this is the important thing) to cast cv once every 10s and cap it at the 140th second, or spam it every 2 seconds and cap it in 28.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
Yes, very good concept on that last paragraph.<br />
<br />
<br />
I wish they would change resists to work as &quot;applies global reuse time only if spell has such, doesnt alter casting time spells.&quot;<br />
<br />
If you get a resist on a spell with a casting time, you have allready paid the time for the resist, and on a instant cast spell, you would pay the global timer of 2 seconds.<br />
<br />
Also, on EQ2 i like how they do casting now, instead of a spell being interupted when your hit, it adds to the casting time, unless the attack explicitly states &quot;interupts target.&quot; Makes having a high channeling skill useful, my Warden is very hard to interupt in a duel. I recall vanguard ahving a simular mechanic but i dont know if it still exists.
                  
		</div>
